 any of several minor places called Haigh in Yorkshire and Lancashire (from Middle English <i>hagh</i> ‘enclosure’, from Old English <i>haga</i> or Old Norse <i>hagi</i>), but especially that in Quarmby, between Huddersfield and Halifax."],"variants":[{"name":"Hague","meanings":["English: variant of   Haigh  .","Irish (Cavan): variant of   Haig  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":13,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":38,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":51,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Anne Haigh was born about 1277, in Lancashire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with John Thomas Prescott."},"et":{"about 1277–":"umbes 1277–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1277–Female":"1277–Surnud","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1275":"1275","about 1277":"umbes 1277","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1277–":"noin 1277–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1277–Female":"1277–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1275":"1275","about 1277":"noin 1277","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1277–":"environ 1277–Décédée","1275–Male":"1275–Décédé","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1277–Female":"1277–Décédée","1315":"1315",